  "prompt": "Are there legal obligations for financial institutions regarding money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, financial institutions have significant legal obligations to prevent, detect, and report money laundering activities. Key requirements typically include:\n\n1. Customer Due Diligence (CDD)\n- Verify customer identities\n- Understand nature of customer's business\n- Assess potential money laundering risks\n\n2. Reporting Requirements\n- File Suspicious Activity Reports (SARs)\n- Report large cash transactions\n- Notify authorities about potential illegal activities\n\n3. Anti-Money Laundering (AML) Programs\n- Develop comprehensive compliance programs\n- Implement internal monitoring systems\n- Conduct regular risk assessments\n- Train employees on detection procedures\n\n4. Record Keeping\n- Maintain transaction records\n- Preserve customer identification documents\n- Retain records for specified periods\n\n5. Compliance with Regulations\n- Follow Bank Secrecy Act (BSA) guidelines\n- Adhere to international anti-money laundering standards\n- Conduct periodic internal and external audits\n\nFailure to meet these obligations can result in significant legal penalties, including substantial fines and potential criminal charges against the institution and responsible individuals.\n\nThese requirements aim to prevent financial crimes and protect the integrity of the global financial system.",
